<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06340157 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06340157 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  AMERICAN-INDIAN; PROTEST; SPORT; NAME; CHANGE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Indian leaders have renewed their call for sports teams to drop Indian namesand symbols.;   &quot;If we can't get white America to understand a basic issue ofhuman respect, how are we going to move on to more substantive issues?&quot; BillMeans, executive director of the Minneapolis-based International Indian TreatyCouncil, asked Wednesday.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  California News  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  INDIANS WANT SPORTS NAMES CHANGEDBRAVES, REDSKINS, CHIEFS ARE ON LIST  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     &quot;We are the only race that are used as mascots.&quot;;   The Atlanta Braves'tomahawk chop and the use of Indian names and symbols by other sports teamsamount to a racist attack on Indian culture, said leaders attending a workshopof the annual convention of the National Congress of American Indians.;   &quot;Ourreligion and tradition need to be recognized, and the negative imagery ofmascots and the commercial use of Indian names create a basis ofmisunderstanding of our people, a misunderstanding which breeds prejudice,&quot;said Michael Haney of the United Indian Nations of Oklahoma,;   In addition tothe Braves, the leaders said the Washington Redskins and the Kansas CityChiefs are on the list of teams that need to make a change.;   Although someIndian leaders have defended the use of the tomahawk chop during the baseballplayoffs and World Series, the majority of Indians oppose such behavior, saidFloyd Red Crow Westerman, an actor who appeared in the movie &quot;Dances WithWolves.&quot;  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Burlingame  </CITY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911205  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Thursday  </DAY><MONTH>  December  </MONTH><PG.COL>  2C  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STAT